{{Infobox meteor shower | name = Zeta Perseids | image = Arietids.gif | imagesize = 255px | caption = Appearance of the eastern sky at 5:00&nbsp;am on June 7, 2000 from a mid-northern latitude observing site. | pronounce = | date = 1947<ref name="Kronk"/> | parent = [[2P/Encke]] ([[Taurids|Taurid Complex]]) <!-- Radiant --> | constellation = [[Perseus (constellation)|Perseus]] <!-- Properties --> | month = {{Nowrap|May 20 – July 5}}<ref name="Kronk"/> | peak = June 9<ref name="IMO2012P"/>–13<ref name="Kronk"/> | velocity = 29<ref name="NASA2000"/> | zhr = 40 (radar)<ref name="Kronk"/> | notes = }}
The '''Zeta Perseids''' (ζ–Perseids) are a daylight [[meteor shower]] that takes place from about May 20 to July 5.<ref name="Kronk"/> The shower was discovered at [[Jodrell Bank Observatory]] in 1947 using radio equipment.<ref name="Kronk"/> The Zeta Perseids and [[Beta Taurids]] are both probably associated with the [[Taurids|Taurid Complex]] of meteor showers.<ref name="IMO2012P"/> The [[Arietids]] and Zeta Perseids maxima tend to blend into one another.<ref name="IMO2012P"/>
